How to Grow Your Telegram Channel Organically A set of guidelines for channels getting started here I have found the best way to real sub growth (not clickbait or spam shit) is to possess and use at least one of three abilities: 1. A unique ability for insight and elocution and post often 2. A unique ability to curate content and post very often 3. A unique ability to create memes/OC and post at least a few times a week My personal ability is clearly 1, Memory Holed does both 1 and 3 extremely well, and Boss Hawg is an absolute wrecking ball of 2 and 3. Now, how do you get started? Well, if you're starting from absolute zero, Telegram makes it really hard to get channel views. Unlike Twitter, the account you use to post to chats and your channel are two separate entities; so your chat posts will seldom lead back to your channel. My suggestion is to choose a few channels you really admire with active attached chats and FIRST participate and build rapport in the groups with the members and hopefully the owners. ONLY AFTER you've spent a significant amount of time participating, making friends, contributing content from other sources, perhaps even being so generous as to sometimes contribute your own OC, or insights or whatever, THEN, OCCASIONALLY share posts from your channel. Don't share every post. Try and make every post count. And don't stop otherwise participating. Your participation to channel share ratio should be at least 20 to 1 at the very minimum. After this, don't be disappointed if your posts are not picked up. You have to put in your work. I sometimes absolutely hate when someone shares a post with me and I don't share it even though I like it. I just can't share every single post that gets posted to the many chats that I have. That said, when someone has real talent and persistence, and they persevere and consistently add value not only by the content of their posts but in their contribution to my chats, I don't know about other content creators but I feel compelled after a while to either share a post or give them a shoutout. It's all about working for free, with no expectation of any reward in return, strictly out of principle. This mindset, paradoxically, always produces the most fruit. @AltSkullMirror

The issue is a key one for companies that have not been identified but that gave information to the Texas attorney general's office for its investigation and fear that their confidential data, like strategic business plans or discussions about negotiations, could be disclosed to Google executives.
